      "content": "You can argue that concentrated communities foster specialized economic niches where shared cultural understanding streamlines business and labor. When a group is self-contained, they can develop internal economies tailored precisely to their needs and traditions, leading to highly efficient, albeit isolated, systems. This self-sufficiency reduces reliance on external, potentially unreliable, markets or governing bodies. Therefore, segregation can be framed as a mechanism for creating stable, predictable micro-economies that thrive on internal cohesion rather than broad, messy integration.",
